      Everything is shareholder derivative claims
   =20
 =20
The basic rule is that when there is a devastating plane crash, the shareho=
lders of the company that makes the plane will sue the company for securiti=
es fraud. =E2=80=9CYou built planes that would crash, but you lied and told=
 everyone that you built planes that wouldn=E2=80=99t crash, and we bought =
your stock thinking your planes wouldn=E2=80=99t crash, and then they did s=
o the stock went down.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t make the rules, and I reali=
ze that this is both bizarre and ghoulish, but it is the rule. =E2=80=9CEve=
rything is securities fraud,=E2=80=9D  I call it. And in fact Boeing Co. ma=
kes=C2=A0planes, including the 737 Max, and in 2019 and 2020 two 737 Max pl=
anes=C2=A0crashed, and Boeing=E2=80=99s=C2=A0stock went down, and sharehold=
ers brought securities fraud lawsuits against it.=C2=A0Standard stuff.=C2=
=A0But there are other, related but slightly different theories. For instan=
ce instead of suing=C2=A0the company=C2=A0for failing to=C2=A0disclose=C2=
=A0that its planes would crash, you could sue=C2=A0the executives and direc=
tors for failing to stop the planes from crashing. =E2=80=9CThe directors a=
nd officers had a fiduciary duty to build safe planes, not planes that cras=
hed, and they failed in their fiduciary duties so they should pay damages.=
=E2=80=9D This sort of lawsuit is called a =E2=80=9Cshareholder derivative =
claim,=E2=80=9D[1] and it is in many ways more complicated than the everyth=
ing-is-securities-fraud theory. It is hard, generally, to get a court to se=
cond-guess directors=E2=80=99 and officers=E2=80=99 business decisions; it =
is hard to hold them personally liable for business failures.But the deriva=
tive lawsuit has=C2=A0some advantages. For one thing, it doesn=E2=80=99t re=
ly on finding misstatements in the disclosure. If Boeing=E2=80=99s public s=
tatements were along the lines of =E2=80=9Cwe try to make safe planes, but =
there is a risk that they might crash due to design flaws, and if they did =
that would be very bad for our business,=E2=80=9D[2] and then some planes c=
rashed, it is a little hard to argue that it=C2=A0deceived=C2=A0anyone. You=
 can, of course =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou said you had a culture of safet=
y and you had a culture of not-safety,=E2=80=9D etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=
=E2=80=99s hard. It seems somehow more straightforward to argue =E2=80=9Clo=
ok, your job was to make safe planes, and you didn=E2=80=99t, so now you ha=
ve to pay.=E2=80=9DFor another thing, if you are a shareholder and you sue =
the company for securities fraud, and you win, the company pays you, which =
is sort of pointless? It just moves money from the corporation (whose share=
s you own) to your bank account, but it was your money anyway. And now the =
lawyers get a chunk of it. But if you sue the directors and win,=C2=A0the m=
oney goes from the directors=E2=80=99 personal accounts to you; money that =
was not yours becomes yours (and the lawyers get a chunk). In practice dire=
ctors are generally indemnified and insurance is paying for all of this, bu=
t it does make a little bit more intuitive sense for shareholders to sue th=
e=C2=A0people=C2=A0who (allegedly) messed up the corporation than it does t=
o sue the corporation itself.Anyway some shareholders brought a derivative =
action against Boeing=E2=80=99s directors and officers, and the directors a=
nd officers asked a Delaware court to dismiss the case, and last week Delaw=
are Vice Chancellor Morgan Zurn ruled that the case against the directors (=
though not the officers[3]) can go forward:The narrow question before this =
Court today is whether Boeing=E2=80=99s stockholders have alleged that a ma=
jority of the Company=E2=80=99s directors face a substantial likelihood of =
liability for Boeing=E2=80=99s losses. This may be based on the directors=
=E2=80=99 complete failure to establish a reporting system for airplane saf=
ety, or on their turning a blind eye to a red flag representing airplane sa=
fety problems. I conclude the stockholders have pled both sources of board =
liability. The stockholders may pursue the Company=E2=80=99s oversight clai=
m against the board.It is hard to sue directors for breaching their fiducia=
ry duties. In general, the =E2=80=9Cbusiness judgment rule=E2=80=9D insulat=
es directors=E2=80=99 business decisions from judicial review. But a 1996 D=
elaware court decision called Caremark allows directors to be held liable f=
or some kinds of failure to oversee the company. Vice Chancellor Zurn expla=
ins:As Chancellor Allen first observed in Caremark, and as since emphasized=
 by this Court many times, perhaps to redundance, the claim that corporate =
fiduciaries have breached their duties to stockholders by failing to monito=
r corporate affairs is =E2=80=9Cpossibly the most difficult theory in corpo=
ration law upon which a plaintiff might hope to win a judgment.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0A decade after Caremark, our Supreme Court affirmed the doctrine Chancel=
lor Allen announced there and clarified that our law will hold directors pe=
rsonally liable only where, in failing to oversee the operations of the com=
pany, =E2=80=9Cthe directors knew that they were not discharging their fidu=
ciary=C2=A0obligations.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0At the pleading stage, a plaintiff mu=
st allege particularized facts that satisfy one of the necessary conditions=
 for director oversight liability articulated in Caremark: either that (1) =
=E2=80=9Cthe directors utterly failed to implement any reporting or informa=
tion system or controls=E2=80=9D; or (2) =E2=80=9Chaving implemented such a=
 system or controls, [the directors] consciously failed to monitor or overs=
ee its operations thus disabling themselves from being informed of risks or=
 problems requiring their attention.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0I respectfully ref=
er to these conditions as Caremark =E2=80=9Cprong one=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9Cprong two.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6As our Supreme Court explained in In re Wal=
t Disney Co. Derivative Litigation, the =E2=80=9Cintentional dereliction of=
 duty=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cconscious disregard for one=E2=80=99s responsibi=
lities,=E2=80=9D which =E2=80=9Cis more culpable than simple inattention or=
 failure to be informed of all facts material to the decision,=E2=80=9D ref=
lects that directors have acted in bad faith and cannot avail themselves of=
 defenses grounded in a presumption of good faith.=C2=A0In order to plead a=
 derivative claim under Caremark, therefore, a plaintiff must plead particu=
larized facts that allow a reasonable inference the directors acted with sc=
ienter which in turn =E2=80=9Crequires [not only] proof that a director act=
ed=C2=A0inconsistent[ly] with his fiduciary duties,=E2=80=9D but also =E2=
=80=9Cmost importantly, that the director knew he was so acting.=E2=80=9DTh=
is is a somewhat strange standard. The words make it sound like the directo=
rs can only be liable if there is proof that they sat around cackling and s=
aying =E2=80=9Cwe don=E2=80=99t care about safety, let it all burn.=E2=80=
=9D But in practice it rarely works like that; instead, mainly the rule is =
that if the board just didn=E2=80=99t pay enough attention to safety, it wi=
ll get in trouble.=C2=A0Here, Boeing=E2=80=99s board =E2=80=9Chad no commit=
tee charged with direct responsibility to monitor airplane safety,=E2=80=9D=
 and =E2=80=9Cdid not regularly allocate meeting time or devote=C2=A0discus=
sion to airplane safety and quality control until after the second crash=E2=
=80=9D:The period after the Lion Air Crash is emblematic of these deficienc=
ies. The Board=E2=80=99s first call on November 23 was explicitly optional.=
 The crash did not appear on the Board=E2=80=99s formal agenda until the Bo=
ard=E2=80=99s regularly scheduled December meeting; those board materials r=
eflect discussion of restoration of profitability and efficiency, but not p=
roduct safety, MCAS, or the AOA sensor.=C2=A0The Audit Committee devoted sl=
ices of five-minute blocks to the crash, through the lens of supply chain, =
factory disruption, and legal issues=E2=80=94not safety.The next board meet=
ing, in February 2019, addressed factory production recovery and a rate inc=
rease, but not product safety or MCAS.=C2=A0At that meeting, the Board affi=
rmatively decided to delay its investigation into the 737 MAX, notwithstand=
ing publicly reported concerns about the airplane=E2=80=99s safety. Weeks l=
ater, after the Ethiopian Airlines Crash,=C2=A0the Board still did not cons=
ider the 737 MAX=E2=80=99s=C2=A0safety. It was not until April 2019=E2=80=
=94after the FAA grounded the 737 MAX fleet=E2=80=94that the Board built in=
 time to address airplane safety.The=C2=A0obvious lessons here are that if =
you are the board of directors of a public company, you should:=09Make a li=
st of the things that can plausibly go horribly wrong at your company.=09Se=
t up a board committee to address each of those things, or perhaps a single=
 committee to address all of them. (The law firm Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & =
Katz, in a client memo about this case, suggests that boards =E2=80=9Cconsi=
der risk management committees tasked with regular review of key enterprise=
 risks.=E2=80=9D[4])=09Make sure you talk about those things at each board =
meeting, and ask management how they are going.=C2=A0=09Have some sort of f=
ormalized reporting and monitoring system: If airplane safety is high on yo=
ur list of worries, you will tell the CEO to write a safety policy, and you=
 will review it, and you will want it to say among other things something l=
ike =E2=80=9Cif anyone at the company sees any safety problem, they can cal=
l this number to report it directly to the board.=E2=80=9DThere is somethin=
g formalistic about these lessons; they all read like ways to avoid legal l=
iability. But also they seem good? Like, the directors are in charge of sup=
ervising the company. They=C2=A0should spend time thinking about what might=
 go horribly wrong, and trying to get the officers to think about those thi=
ngs, and putting structures in place to prevent those things. If Boeing=E2=
=80=99s board had spent 20 minutes at each meeting talking about safety, wo=
uld that have prevented the 737 Max crashes? Probably not, no. But maybe? A=
t least with the benefit of hindsight, =E2=80=9CBoeing=E2=80=99s board shou=
ld have thought more about safety=E2=80=9D does seem like good advice?The w=
hole thing of shareholders suing when terrible things happen at a company i=
s always embarrassing. In this case, Vice Chancellor Zurn has to start by a=
pologizing for the triviality of treating shareholders as the victims:The p=
rimary victims of the crashes are, of course, the deceased, their families,=
 and their loved ones. While it may seem callous in the face of their losse=
s, corporate law recognizes another set of victims: Boeing as an enterprise=
, and its stockholders. The crashes caused the Company and its investors to=
 lose billions of dollars in value. Stockholders have come to this Court cl=
aiming Boeing=E2=80=99s directors and officers failed them in overseeing mi=
ssion-critical airplane safety to protect enterprise and stockholder value.=
=C2=A0But at least it makes a little bit more sense here than in the everyt=
hing-is-securities-fraud cases. For one thing, suing the=C2=A0directors=C2=
=A0is a better deterrent than suing=C2=A0the corporation.=C2=A0Directors ar=
e going to care more about being held personally liable (even if they=E2=80=
=99re indemnified, etc.) than they are about the company losing a bit more =
money in shareholder settlements on top of the money it already lost from t=
he bad event itself.For another thing, though, here you are at least suing =
about the right sorts of stuff. In everything-is-securities-fraud cases, th=
e allegation is always =E2=80=9Cyou said you try to=C2=A0do good things, bu=
t you did bad things,=E2=80=9D and the simple solution is to=C2=A0stop sayi=
ng you do good things.=C2=A0If shareholders  sue you for not living up to y=
our aspirational  diversity policy, get rid of the diversity policy. But he=
re, the allegation is =E2=80=9Cyou should do a better job of making sure th=
at the company doesn=E2=80=99t do bad things.=E2=80=9D And the only way to =
address that is by doing your job.
