      Supply chain finance
   =20
 =20
Here is a  Bloomberg Businessweek story from last week about Greensill Capi=
tal. It includes this quick summary of how Greensill=E2=80=99s business was=
 supposed to work (it  did not always work this way):Greensill Capital had =
the melon farm. Lex Greensill, founder and chief executive officer of the L=
ondon-based lender that proclaimed it was =E2=80=9Cmaking finance fairer,=
=E2=80=9D loved regaling anyone within earshot about his parents scratching=
 out a living in the flatlands around Bundaberg, Australia. A good harvest =
of melons and sugar cane meant fat times, but a dry year could wreak havoc.=
 Just as stressful were the monthslong delays in payments from customers, l=
eaving the family short of cash. In Greensill=E2=80=99s telling, his compan=
y had come up with a way to help small businesspeople like his parents get =
their money faster.Greensill offered a version of something called supply c=
hain finance, an arcane corner of banking in which a middleman pays a suppl=
ier immediately, but at a discount, and then collects the full amount from =
the buyer a few months later. Greensill Capital=E2=80=99s technology, the c=
ompany said, could assess the risk of loans with the help of artificial int=
elligence. Rather than making all these loans with its own cash, Greensill =
Capital often sold the IOUs it arranged to outside investors, who saw them =
as a way to earn better-than-average returns with virtually no risk. After =
all, the loans were based on sales that had already happened=E2=80=94Greens=
ill was merely working out a kink in the cash flow.Here=E2=80=99s a story a=
bout a big company that provides short-term financing for small businesses =
secured against those businesses=E2=80=99 accounts receivable. That company=
 is Facebook Inc.:Facebook [last] week announced a $100 million commitment =
to a program that supports small businesses owned by women and minorities b=
y buying up their outstanding invoices.By buying up outstanding invoices, t=
he Facebook Invoice Fast Track program puts money in the hands of small bus=
inesses that would have otherwise had to wait weeks if not months to get pa=
id by their customers.=C2=A0The program is the latest effort by Facebook to=
 build its relationships and long-term loyalty among small businesses, many=
 of whom rely on the social network to place ads targeted to niche demograp=
hics who may be interested in their services.=C2=A0Businesses can submit ou=
tstanding invoices of a minimum of $1,000, and if accepted, Facebook will b=
uy the invoice from the small business and pay them within a matter of days=
. The customers then pay Facebook the outstanding invoices at the same term=
s they had agreed to with the small business. For Facebook, which generated=
 nearly $86 billion in revenue in 2020, waiting for payments is much less d=
ire than it is for small businesses.=C2=A0Okay so there is a business of (1=
) using artificial intelligence to evaluate the payment risk involved in in=
voices, (2) advancing cash against those invoices, and (3) trying to make s=
ure they get paid back. My questions are:=09Who has better AI technology: F=
acebook or this Australian ex-melon farmer?=09Who has cheaper access to cas=
h?=09Who has more leverage to get paid back?I dunno, how do you compete wit=
h Facebook? =E2=80=9CEvery bank wants to be a tech company, but every tech =
company wants to be a bank,=E2=80=9D[5] and it does seem like the tech gian=
ts have some key advantages if they want to get into banking. For one thing=
, they are good at data and so forth. For another thing, so much of commerc=
e runs through them anyway. Also though they are kind of where the money is=
.In the most general terms, if you are a small business and you need financ=
ing, whom should you ask for financing? The traditional answer is that you =
ask your bank, but that answer feels pass=C3=A9 nowadays; banks are stodgy =
and slow-moving and risk-averse. The modern answer is that you ask some sor=
t of specialized finance company, like Greensill or like =E2=80=9Cmerchant =
cash advance=E2=80=9D companies. But these are often expensive, and there a=
re some search costs involved in you finding them or them finding you. The =
postmodern answer is, like, =E2=80=9Cwe sell all our products by buying ads=
 on a couple of big tech platforms, we might as well see if they=E2=80=99ll=
 give us money too.=E2=80=9D Sometimes they will.=C2=A0
