10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Everything is shareholder derivative claims</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic rule is that when there is a=
 devastating plane crash, the shareholders of the company that makes the pl=
ane will sue the company for securities fraud. =E2=80=9CYou built planes th=
at would crash, but you lied and told everyone that you built planes that w=
ouldn=E2=80=99t crash, and we bought your stock thinking your planes wouldn=
=E2=80=99t crash, and then they did so the stock went down.=E2=80=9D I don=
=E2=80=99t make the rules, and I realize that this is both bizarre and ghou=
lish, but it is the rule. =E2=80=9CEverything is securities fraud,=E2=80=9D=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25029699.260586/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDMvZ29s=
ZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9uLWdhbWV=
zdG9wLWtrcG9lNndz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2cecbcc9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I call it</a>. And in fact Boei=
ng Co. makes=C2=A0planes, including the 737 Max, and in 2019 and 2020 <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25029699.260586/aHR0cHM=
6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQm9laW5nXzczN19NQVhfZ3JvdW5kaW5ncw/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB8ca7e770" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">two 737 Max planes=C2=A0crashed</a>, and Boeing=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0stock went down, and shareholders <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/25029699.260586/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2FzaGluZ3RvbnBvc3QuY=
29tL2J1c2luZXNzLzIwMTkvMDQvMTAvYm9laW5nLXNoYXJlaG9sZGVyLWZpbGVzLWNsYXNzLWFj=
dGlvbi1sYXdzdWl0LWFsbGVnZXMtcGxhbmUtbWFrZXItY29uY2VhbGVkLW1heC1zYWZldHktcml=
za3Mv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbfe6c0f9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">brought securities fraud lawsuits</a> agai=
nst it.=C2=A0Standard stuff.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But ther=
e are other, related but slightly different theories. For instance instead =
of suing=C2=A0<em>the company=C2=A0</em>for failing to=C2=A0<em>disclose=C2=
=A0</em>that its planes would crash, you could sue=C2=A0<em>the executives =
and directors </em>for failing to<em> stop the planes from crashing</em>. =
=E2=80=9CThe directors and officers had a fiduciary duty to build safe plan=
es, not planes that crashed, and they failed in their fiduciary duties so t=
hey should pay damages.=E2=80=9D This sort of lawsuit is called a =E2=80=9C=
shareholder derivative claim,=E2=80=9D[1] and it is in many ways more compl=
icated than the everything-is-securities-fraud theory. It is hard, generall=
y, to get a court to second-guess directors=E2=80=99 and officers=E2=80=99 =
business decisions; it is hard to hold them personally liable for business =
failures.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the derivative lawsuit has=C2=
=A0some advantages. For one thing, it doesn=E2=80=99t rely on finding misst=
atements in the disclosure. If Boeing=E2=80=99s public statements were alon=
g the lines of =E2=80=9Cwe try to make safe planes, but there is a risk tha=
t they might crash due to design flaws, and if they did that would be very =
bad for our business,=E2=80=9D[2] and then some planes crashed, it is a lit=
tle hard to argue that it=C2=A0<em>deceived=C2=A0</em>anyone. You can, of c=
ourse =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou said you had a culture of safety and you =
had a culture of not-safety,=E2=80=9D etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s =
hard. It seems somehow more straightforward to argue =E2=80=9Clook, your jo=
b was to make safe planes, and you didn=E2=80=99t, so now you have to pay.=
=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For another thing, if you are a s=
hareholder and you sue the company for securities fraud, and you win, the c=
ompany pays you, which is sort of pointless? It just moves money from the c=
orporation (whose shares you own) to your bank account, but it was your mon=
ey anyway. And now the lawyers get a chunk of it. But if you sue the direct=
ors and win,=C2=A0the money goes from the directors=E2=80=99 personal accou=
nts to you; money that was not yours becomes yours (and the lawyers get a c=
hunk). In practice directors are generally indemnified and insurance is pay=
ing for all of this, but it does make a little bit more intuitive sense for=
 shareholders to sue the=C2=A0<em>people=C2=A0</em>who (allegedly) messed u=
p the corporation than it does to sue the corporation itself.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway some shareholders brought a derivative action a=
gainst Boeing=E2=80=99s directors and officers, and the directors and offic=
ers asked a Delaware court to dismiss the case, and last week <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25029699.260586/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3V=
ydHMuZGVsYXdhcmUuZ292L09waW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg_aWQ9MzI0MTIw/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB58f27251" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">Delaware Vice Chancellor Morgan Zurn ruled</a> that the cas=
e against the directors (though not the officers[3]) can go forward:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The narrow question before this Court=
 today is whether Boeing=E2=80=99s stockholders have alleged that a majorit=
y of the Company=E2=80=99s directors face a substantial likelihood of liabi=
lity for Boeing=E2=80=99s losses. This may be based on the directors=E2=80=
=99 complete failure to establish a reporting system for airplane safety, o=
r on their turning a blind eye to a red flag representing airplane safety p=
roblems. I conclude the stockholders have pled both sources of board liabil=
ity. The stockholders may pursue the Company=E2=80=99s oversight claim agai=
nst the board.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is hard to s=
ue directors for breaching their fiduciary duties. In general, the =E2=80=
=9Cbusiness judgment rule=E2=80=9D insulates directors=E2=80=99 business de=
cisions from judicial review. But a 1996 Delaware court decision called Car=
emark allows directors to be held liable for some kinds of failure to overs=
ee the company. Vice Chancellor Zurn explains:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">As Chancellor Allen first observed in <em>Caremark</em>, an=
d as since emphasized by this Court many times, perhaps to redundance, the =
claim that corporate fiduciaries have breached their duties to stockholders=
 by failing to monitor corporate affairs is =E2=80=9Cpossibly the most diff=
icult theory in corporation law upon which a plaintiff might hope to win a =
judgment.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0A decade after <em>Caremark</em>, our Supreme Court=
 affirmed the doctrine Chancellor Allen announced there and clarified that =
our law will hold directors personally liable only where, in failing to ove=
rsee the operations of the company, =E2=80=9Cthe directors knew that they w=
ere not discharging their fiduciary=C2=A0obligations.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0At the =
pleading stage, a plaintiff must allege particularized facts that satisfy o=
ne of the necessary conditions for director oversight liability articulated=
 in <em>Caremark</em>: either that (1) =E2=80=9Cthe directors utterly faile=
d to implement any reporting or information system or controls=E2=80=9D; or=
 (2) =E2=80=9Chaving implemented such a system or controls, [the directors]=
 consciously failed to monitor or oversee its operations thus disabling the=
mselves from being informed of risks or problems requiring their attention.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0I respectfully refer to these conditions as <em>Carema=
rk </em>=E2=80=9Cprong one=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cprong two.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As our Supreme Court explained in In re=
 <em>Walt Disney Co. Derivative Litigation</em>, the =E2=80=9Cintentional d=
ereliction of duty=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cconscious disregard for one=E2=80=
=99s responsibilities,=E2=80=9D which =E2=80=9Cis more culpable than simple=
 inattention or failure to be informed of all facts material to the decisio=
n,=E2=80=9D reflects that directors have acted in bad faith and cannot avai=
l themselves of defenses grounded in a presumption of good faith.=C2=A0In o=
rder to plead a derivative claim under <em>Caremark</em>, therefore, a plai=
ntiff must plead particularized facts that allow a reasonable inference the=
 directors acted with scienter which in turn =E2=80=9Crequires [not only] p=
roof that a director acted=C2=A0inconsistent[ly] with his fiduciary duties,=
=E2=80=9D but also =E2=80=9Cmost importantly, that the director knew he was=
 so acting.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a=
 somewhat strange standard. The words make it sound like the directors can =
only be liable if there is proof that they sat around cackling and saying =
=E2=80=9Cwe don=E2=80=99t care about safety, let it all burn.=E2=80=9D But =
in practice it rarely works like that; instead, mainly the rule is that if =
the board just didn=E2=80=99t pay enough attention to safety, it will get i=
n trouble.=C2=A0Here, Boeing=E2=80=99s board =E2=80=9Chad no committee char=
ged with direct responsibility to monitor airplane safety,=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9Cdid not regularly allocate meeting time or devote=C2=A0discussion to =
airplane safety and quality control until after the second crash=E2=80=9D:<=
/p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The period after the Lion Air C=
rash is emblematic of these deficiencies. The Board=E2=80=99s first call on=
 November 23 was explicitly optional. The crash did not appear on the Board=
=E2=80=99s formal agenda until the Board=E2=80=99s regularly scheduled Dece=
mber meeting; those board materials reflect discussion of restoration of pr=
ofitability and efficiency, but not product safety, MCAS, or the AOA sensor=
.=C2=A0The Audit Committee devoted slices of five-minute blocks to the cras=
h, through the lens of supply chain, factory disruption, and legal issues=
=E2=80=94not safety.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The next board meeting=
, in February 2019, addressed factory production recovery and a rate increa=
se, but not product safety or MCAS.=C2=A0At that meeting, the Board affirma=
tively decided to delay its investigation into the 737 MAX, notwithstanding=
 publicly reported concerns about the airplane=E2=80=99s safety. Weeks late=
r, after the Ethiopian Airlines Crash,=C2=A0the Board still did not conside=
r the 737 MAX=E2=80=99s=C2=A0safety. It was not until April 2019=E2=80=94af=
ter the FAA grounded the 737 MAX fleet=E2=80=94that the Board built in time=
 to address airplane safety.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">T=
he=C2=A0obvious lessons here are that if you are the board of directors of =
a public company, you should:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; pad=
ding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Make=
 a list of the things that can plausibly go horribly wrong at your company.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Set up a board committee to addre=
ss each of those things, or perhaps a single committee to address all of th=
em. (The law firm Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &amp; Katz, in a client memo abou=
t this case, suggests that boards =E2=80=9Cconsider risk management committ=
ees tasked with regular review of key enterprise risks.=E2=80=9D[4])</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Make sure you talk about those things =
at each board meeting, and ask management how they are going.=C2=A0</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Have some sort of formalized reporting an=
d monitoring system: If airplane safety is high on your list of worries, yo=
u will tell the CEO to write a safety policy, and you will review it, and y=
ou will want it to say among other things something like =E2=80=9Cif anyone=
 at the company sees any safety problem, they can call this number to repor=
t it directly to the board.=E2=80=9D</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
There is something formalistic about these lessons; they all read like ways=
 to avoid legal liability. But also they seem good? Like, the directors are=
 in charge of supervising the company. They=C2=A0<em>should </em>spend time=
 thinking about what might go horribly wrong, and trying to get the officer=
s to think about those things, and putting structures in place to prevent t=
hose things. If Boeing=E2=80=99s board had spent 20 minutes at each meeting=
 talking about safety, would that have prevented the 737 Max crashes? Proba=
bly not, no. But maybe? At least with the benefit of hindsight, =E2=80=9CBo=
eing=E2=80=99s board should have thought more about safety=E2=80=9D does se=
em like good advice?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The whole thing of sha=
reholders suing when terrible things happen at a company is always embarras=
sing. In this case, Vice Chancellor Zurn has to start by apologizing for th=
e triviality of treating shareholders as the victims:</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The primary victims of the crashes are, of course, t=
he deceased, their families, and their loved ones. While it may seem callou=
s in the face of their losses, corporate law recognizes another set of vict=
ims: Boeing as an enterprise, and its stockholders. The crashes caused the =
Company and its investors to lose billions of dollars in value. Stockholder=
s have come to this Court claiming Boeing=E2=80=99s directors and officers =
failed them in overseeing mission-critical airplane safety to protect enter=
prise and stockholder value.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">But at least it makes a little bit more sense here than in the everyth=
ing-is-securities-fraud cases. For one thing, suing the=C2=A0<em>directors=
=C2=A0</em>is a better deterrent than suing=C2=A0<em>the corporation.</em>=
=C2=A0Directors are going to care more about being held personally liable (=
even if they=E2=80=99re indemnified, etc.) than they are about the company =
losing a bit more money in shareholder settlements on top of the money it a=
lready lost from the bad event itself.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For =
another thing, though, here you are at least suing about the right sorts of=
 stuff. In everything-is-securities-fraud cases, the allegation is always =
=E2=80=9Cyou said you try to=C2=A0do good things, but you did bad things,=
=E2=80=9D and the simple solution is to=C2=A0<em>stop saying you do good th=
ings.=C2=A0</em>If shareholders <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/25029699.260586/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDctMjAvdGhleS1yZS1hbGwtZnJpZW5kcy1pbi10aGUtaW5kZXg/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB46b440a1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> sue you</a> for not living up to your aspirational <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25029699.260586/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDctMTMvd2UtaGF=
zLWRlY2lkZWQtdG8tbWFrZS1tb25leQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf0c2f784" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> diversity policy<=
/a>, get rid of the diversity policy. But here, the allegation is =E2=80=9C=
you should do a better job of making sure that the company doesn=E2=80=99t =
do bad things.=E2=80=9D And the only way to address that is by doing your j=
ob.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpad=
