<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Private markets are the new public markets</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or not. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/25029699.260586/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRp=
Y2xlcy9wcmUtaXBvLW1hcmtldHBsYWNlLWZvcmdlLWdsb2JhbC10by1nby1wdWJsaWMtaW4tMi1=
iaWxsaW9uLXNwYWMtZGVhbC0xMTYzMTUzMDgwMA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa84cc75f" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">But</a>:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Forge Global Inc., an online mar=
ketplace for buying and selling shares of private firms, plans to go public=
 by merging with a special-purpose acquisition company.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">The deal with Motive Capital Corp. values the resulting compan=
y at $2 billion, the companies said. If completed, the transaction would ma=
ke Forge the first dedicated trading platform for private shares to become =
a public company.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading in private shares=
 has heated up in recent years as startups have waited longer to hold initi=
al public offerings. Such trading allows employees to cash out of their sha=
res and lets some investors get early access to potentially fast-growing te=
chnology startups.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most individual investor=
s aren=E2=80=99t able to buy shares on Forge or other trading platforms for=
 pre-IPO stock. Under Securities and Exchange Commission rules, such deals =
are typically limited to accredited investors=E2=80=94people who meet certa=
in wealth criteria, such as having a net worth of more than $1 million, exc=
luding one=E2=80=99s home, or an annual income above $200,000.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe public markets need an investment that is=
 a proxy for the private markets,=E2=80=9D Forge Chief Executive Kelly Rodr=
iques said in an interview. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s Forge.=E2=80=9D</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is interesting about the Forge d=
eal is that it provides some public information about private-company tradi=
ng. (Or, at least, about the trading of private companies on Forge=E2=80=99=
s platform.) Here is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/25029699.260586/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRh=
LzE4Mjc4MjEvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMTE0OTA1L3RtMjEyNzQyMGQxX2V4OTktMi5odG0/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB4699e876" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">investor presentation</a> that Forge and Motive filed tod=
ay. Forge claims that there are 762 unicorns =E2=80=94=C2=A0venture-backed =
private companies with a valuation of at least $1 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0in=
 the world, of which 142 have traded on its platform in the last year. But =
they don=E2=80=99t trade that much:=C2=A0</p><!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/ikwm0NQqxFXM/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/ikwm0NQqxFXM/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The average public company trades =
126% of its market capitalization every year; a billion-dollar public compa=
ny will do about $1.26 billion of stock-market volume per year, or about $5=
 million=C2=A0per day. The average private company (on Forge) trades about =
0.2% of its value per year (on Forge); a billion-dollar unicorn will do abo=
ut $2 million worth of trading in a year. Forge has traded $10 billion of p=
rivate-company stock since its inception; Tesla Inc.=E2=80=99s stock traded=
 $11.4 billion on Friday.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CPrivate =
markets are the new public markets,=E2=80=9D I like to say around here; tha=
nks to modern technology and global capital markets,=C2=A0private companies=
 can offer their shareholders much better liquidity than they could get in =
the past. But still not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>much. The average private c=
ompany still has less liquidity in a year than the average public company d=
oes in a day. Trading private-company stock remains a special occasion; you=
 can sometimes line up a secondary trade with another venture fund or hedge=
 fund, or buy stock from employees in a tender offer, but it=E2=80=99s not =
just a matter of putting in an order on the exchange.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Also while private-company trades are infrequent, they are also =
expensive:</p><!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/iHeXoyBh1RG8/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/iHeXoyBh1RG8/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In public markets, brokers and who=
lesalers and exchanges compete fiercely and controversially over fractions =
of pennies to execute trades. In the private market Forge makes about 2.5% =
or 3%.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t want to sugges=
t that public stock markets are perfect, but they are, in some sense,=C2=A0=
<em>perfected</em>. A lot of the large-scale problems are solved, and very =
smart people compete fiercely to execute trades 1 millisecond faster than e=
ach other. You can trade as much stock as you want, basically instantaneous=
ly and basically for free, and even the problem=C2=A0of <em>picking which s=
tocks to buy</em>=C2=A0is so thoroughly analyzed at this point that lots of=
 people just index. Public stock markets are boring, in the sense that the =
low-hanging fruit has largely been plucked, and there is a lot of intense c=
ompetition over basis points and plumbing.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">One thing that you could do is embrace this and work to shave half a =
basis point off your index fund=E2=80=99s expense ratio, but another very p=
opular approach is to abandon traditional public markets for places where t=
he problems are less solved. You could get into crypto, for instance. As an=
 investor (because some cryptocurrencies go up a lot), sure; but providing =
various services in crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0running an exchange, running a ma=
rket maker, constructing derivatives =E2=80=94=C2=A0also seems to be a lot =
more lucrative than providing those services in the transparent, well-under=
stood, boring traditional financial markets. Similarly, if you are investin=
g in=C2=A0the private markets you can put some money into a tiny startup th=
at will be the next Facebook. Or you can provide the platform for trading t=
hat company=E2=80=99s stock and collect 3%.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-f=
lex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
<tr>
