<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Supply chain finance</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25029699.260586/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDgvd2h5LWRpZC1ncmVlbnNpbGwtY29sbGFwc2Utd=
GhlLXNpbXBsZS1wcm9ibGVtLWJlaGluZC10aGUtZmluYW5jaWFsLWVtcGlyZQ/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB9848c77e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> Bloomberg Businessweek story</a> from last week about Greensi=
ll Capital. It includes this quick summary of how Greensill=E2=80=99s busin=
ess was supposed to work (it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/25029699.260586/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMTcvZ3JlZW5zaWxsLWRpZG4tdC1qdXN0LWZpbmFuY2UtYmx1ZXN0b25=
lLXMtc3VwcGx5LWNoYWlu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe71f96a0" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> did not always work this wa=
y</a>):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Greensill Capital had t=
he melon farm. Lex Greensill, founder and chief executive officer of the Lo=
ndon-based lender that proclaimed it was =E2=80=9Cmaking finance fairer,=E2=
=80=9D loved regaling anyone within earshot about his parents scratching ou=
t a living in the flatlands around Bundaberg, Australia. A good harvest of =
melons and sugar cane meant fat times, but a dry year could wreak havoc. Ju=
st as stressful were the monthslong delays in payments from customers, leav=
ing the family short of cash. In Greensill=E2=80=99s telling, his company h=
ad come up with a way to help small businesspeople like his parents get the=
ir money faster.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Greensill offered a versio=
n of something called supply chain finance, an arcane corner of banking in =
which a middleman pays a supplier immediately, but at a discount, and then =
collects the full amount from the buyer a few months later. Greensill Capit=
al=E2=80=99s technology, the company said, could assess the risk of loans w=
ith the help of artificial intelligence. Rather than making all these loans=
 with its own cash, Greensill Capital often sold the IOUs it arranged to ou=
tside investors, who saw them as a way to earn better-than-average returns =
with virtually no risk. After all, the loans were based on sales that had a=
lready happened=E2=80=94Greensill was merely working out a kink in the cash=
 flow.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a story =
about a big company that provides short-term financing for small businesses=
 secured against those businesses=E2=80=99 accounts receivable. That compan=
